## Level 30 → Level 31
**Objective:** Find the password hidden in a git tag — not in the
files, commit history, or branches.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
git clone ssh://bandit30-git@bandit.labs.overthewire.org:2220/home/bandit30-git/repo bandit30repo
cd bandit30repo
cat README.md                   # "just an empty file... muahaha"
git log                         # nothing useful in commit history
git branch -a                   # no other branches besides master
git tag                         # listed tags — found "secret"
git show secret                 # revealed the password
```

**What is a Git Tag?**
- A tag is a label attached to a specific point in git history
- Usually used to mark important versions like releases
  e.g. `v1.0`, `v2.3`, `release-2024`
- Unlike branches, tags don't change — they point to one fixed commit
- Tags can also store arbitrary data — like a password in this case
- Not shown in `git log` by default — easy to miss

**Types of Git Tags:**
| Type | Description |
|---|---|
| Lightweight tag | Just a pointer to a commit — like a bookmark |
| Annotated tag | Contains extra data — message, author, date |

**Why Tags Are Interesting in Pentesting:**
- Tags are often overlooked when investigating repositories
- Developers use tags to mark releases — which may contain
  old credentials or sensitive configuration
- Annotated tags can store messages with sensitive information
- Tags persist even when branches are deleted

**The Full Git Investigation Checklist (Updated):**
```bash
cat README.md               # 1. check obvious files
git log                     # 2. check commit history
git branch -a               # 3. check all branches
git tag                     # 4. check all tags ← new this level
git show tagname            # 5. examine tag contents
git show commitID           # 6. examine specific commits
```

**What I Learned:**
- Git has three main places to hide data:
  - Commit history (`git log` + `git show`)
  - Branches (`git branch -a` + `git checkout`)
  - Tags (`git tag` + `git show`) ← new this level
- Tags are not visible in `git log` — need separate command
- `git show` works on both commit IDs and tag names
- Always run all three checks when investigating a repository

**Real Pentesting Relevance:**
Git tags are commonly used to mark production releases — making
them high value targets in pentesting:
- Release tags often contain production configuration
- Tags named `v1.0`, `release`, `prod` are worth checking
- Some developers store deployment notes in annotated tags
- Tags survive branch deletions — old sensitive data persists

**Key Takeaway:**
A complete git investigation requires checking commits, branches
AND tags. Missing any one of these three could mean missing the
sensitive data you are looking for. Always run all three commands
as part of your standard git reconnaissance process.
